SIMPLE: winch
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Winch
<hw>Winch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Wince</er>.]</ety> <def>To wince; to shrink; to kick with impatience
or uneasiness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Winch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Winch
<hw>Winch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A kick, as of a beast, from
impatience or uneasiness.</def> <rj><au>Shelton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Winch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Winch
<hw>Winch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>winche</ets>, AS.
<ets>wince</ets> a winch, a reel to wind thread upon. Cf.
<er>Wink</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A crank with a handle, for giving motion to a
machine, a grindstone, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An instrument with which to turn or strain something
forcibly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An axle or drum turned by a crank with a handle, or
by power, for raising weights, as from the hold of a ship, from mines,
etc.; a windlass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A wince.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1655 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wincing</ent>⟦br⟧
